TY  - JOUR
AU  - Yang, Wei
T1  -  Intertemporal Substitution and Equity Premium *
PY  - 2016
Y1  - 2016/03/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfv004
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 20
IS  - 1
SP  - 403
EP  - 445
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - This article presents a model that incorporates habit formation and long-run risks into the Epstein–Zin preferences, and reveals intertemporal substitution as a distinctive channel, separate from risk aversion, in generating key asset market phenomena. With habit formation, both the risk aversion and intertemporal substitution channels enhance the market price of short-run consumption risk. With long-run risks, intertemporal substitution reduces the market prices of long-run consumption risks, working against risk aversion. The contrasting effects of the intertemporal substitution channel drive key differences in the model implications of habit formation and long-run risks.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfv004
ER  - 



